The paper deals with lower bounds for computational models such as branching programs, Boolean formulas, and circuits, which are typically studied in the computational complexity (cs.CC) and data structures (cs.DS) sub-categories. The problem of orthogonal vectors is also related to computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM), as it involves vectors in high-dimensional spaces. Finally, the paper uses information theory techniques to prove its results, which suggests a connection to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
